x4freetext: Spectrometer described
Prompt gamma-ray spectra and integrated cross sections
for the radiative capture of 14 MeV neutrons for
28 natural targets in the mass region from 12 to 208
Cockcroft-Walton accelerator, energy of
incident deuteron is 100 keV.
T(d,n)He-4 reaction.
The ``energy-spread`` is 1.35 MeV,that is +- 0.675 MeV.
Natural or mono-isotopic compositions. Samples are
spheres and/or hemispheres of 4-6 cm diameter placed
close to the tritium target. Therefore the neutron
energy is spread over a range from 13.5 to 14.7 MeV.
Due to this geometry the spectra obtained are
integrated over a solid angle of 2(4) pi
Gamma spectra were measured with the telescopic
scintillation pair spectrometer.
Recoil proton spectrometer was used for neutron
monitoring.
The energy resolution of gammas has been determined
by the energy width of the spectrometer response
function (1.65+-0.05MeV)and by the energy spread of the
neutron beam (1.35 MeV). The resulting resolutions are
14% at 15 MeV, and 10% at 21 MeV.
Scintillation pair spectrometer of which
resolution has been measured to be 12.5, 9.5 and 8.0%
for gammas of energies 12.1,16.5 and 20.4 MeV,
respectively.
Efficiencies for these gamma energies have been
measured to be 0.45,0.55 and 0.56%,respectively.
.Recoil proton spectrometer using a CsI(Tl) crystal
for neutron-flux monitoring.  The accuracy of the
determination of the neutron flux was +- 6%.
The integrated capture cross sections are obtained by
integration of the fully corrected gamma spectrum over
the excitation energy interval up to the binding
energy of the last neutron in the final nucleus
Absolute measurements
This entry supersedes the following earlier entries:
Data taken from rept. INDC(YUG)-6(1979), Tbl.2.
Spectra were corrected for
.background,
.the spectrometer response function,
.the gammas created and absorbed in the sample,
.absorption of gammas in the paraffin-collimator, and
.neutron nonelastic processes in the target.
The overall error includes the uncertainties:
. due to statistical errors,
. on the background correction,
(7% for spheres,  1% for hemispheres),
. due to spectrometer response function
which enlarges statistical error by a factor of 1.8,
. on the energy scale (2% at 14 MeV, 3% at 22 MeV),
on the spectrometer efficiency of 11%,
on the correction for absorption of gammas, 1%.
on the correction for nonelastic processes
in the target,  2%,
on the neutron flux,  6%,
on the anisotropy of gammas, 3%,
due to the assumption of equal solid angle for
the whole sample, 1%.
The resulting error for the cross-sections was about
